         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a_2"/><w>ṣiyai</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b_2"/><w>went<supplied>s</supplied></w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a_2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">slime</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b_2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">excrement</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a_2" type="lingcomment">This word is so far unattested; perhaps the reading should be <hi>ṣiy[aiñe]</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a_2" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>khe(ṭaḥ)</hi> 'phlegm, slime'.</note><note corresp="#b_2" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>gū(tha)</hi> 'excrement'. Although a tiny trace of the long <hi>ū</hi> of <hi>gū(tha)</hi> is readable (<bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2012"/><citedRange>374</citedRange></bibl> reads <hi>g[u]</hi> ///), the reading of the Sanskrit text is here clearly made possible by the Tocharian gloss.</note></p>
         </div>
